I received the most lovely gift from @laurie3.14 ! If you’re not familiar with Laurie, she’s an extremely prolific quilter who hand quilts her makes and tracks her progress almost down to the stitch. (It always amazes me because I have a very sketchy relationship with any kind of math.) She has a goal to have her quilts in each of the fifty states, and I was able to “help” her out here in West Virginia. 

This quilt drapes, moves and cuddles so well! I’m drawn to each piece of fabric. So many things to find! There are even a few that I have in my own stash and recognize as “mine.” (Do you do that, too?) The colors make my eyes very happy. I am so thankful for Laurie and her creative way of quilting and counting! #quilt #handquilting #quilting #fabric #giftquilt #quilter

I’ve been receiving the signature slips I requested from family members for our future #familysignaturequilt and today’s mail had a surprise that actually made me cry. I included a scrap of the wash-away material to test your pen on and an extra signature sized sheet just in case of mistakes. My Mom used the extra sheet to reproduce her parents’ signatures for our quilt. My Grandma has been gone over 20 years, and Paw-Paw for … 30some? It was an idea I hadn’t considered, but now I want my other grandparents on the quilt, and my uncles who are gone … Is it OK to add people when they can’t consent? I do love the idea of having them on the quilt along with the newest generation that they never met. I really want this. 
#quilt #quiltplanning #signaturequilt #familyquilt #autographquilt

After Mom sent me her parents’ signatures for our future #familysignaturequilt , I knew I wanted to include Dad’s parents, too. (Mom’s are in the second photo.)

I went to @ancestry and found Grandad’s draft card pretty quickly. Women’s historical signatures are much harder to find. Thankfully I had Googled Grandma’s name ages ago (as you do, right?) and found the pages where her marriage to Grandad was recorded — in her writing! I’d saved that, thankfully, because the online source seems to have disappeared. The bottom version is where I patched the pieces together, including reordering Grandma’s signature, and the top is what will be used in the quilt. 

#signaturequilt #autographquilt #quilt #familyheirloom #ancestry

Yesterday I lost my best friend, Mojo. He was having too much pain, even combinations of pills weren’t enough anymore, and I didn’t want to let him hurt. Here are a couple of my favorite pics of him, meeting Percy for the first time and at Petco when I told him to pick out a treat. 🤣 The last photo is the last photo I took of him. 

My brother lost his dog, my nephew Cash, this week, too. It’s been tough.

My little hoodlums seem to recognize my loss of Mojo and have formed a cat support posse of sorts. Fluffy beast care helps. 

Mako, on the other hand, hasn’t seemed to miss her bestie at all. At least until feeding time. She ate hers and then went to his place to clean his bowl, too, and was dumbfounded that there was no second bowl. She could not understand why. 

#petloss #petlosssupport

Sundays after church, a group of us have breakfast at a friend’s woodworking mill. There are two cats there, and one has adopted me. She knows when it’s Sunday morning, she comes up to the office and finds me. After I eat she snuggles in my lap, covering me in fur and sawdust. I’ve named her Pearl. #factorycat #cats

Without Mojo, I don’t trust Mako not to run off if given the opportunity. (Mojo knew not to and she wouldn’t leave if he didn’t.) I bought her an iTag for her collar so I can find her if she bolts. She’s microchipped, but that only allows a shelter or vet to identify her. I want to be able to find her FAST. 

We’re also working on discipline. I’ve explained to her that she now has dog seniority and that more is expected of her. (Discipline is not fun. Mako prefers FUN.) She did manage not to jump all over my Dad when he stopped by, but it took so much reminding her. We’re getting there. #dog #dogs #dogtraining

Making my own stationery to write to a new pen pal. Through @orderofmalta_official I’ve been connected to two prisoners who have requested pen pals. Does the idea make you uncomfortable? 

Through their program, my address isn’t revealed and both sides have agreed this is only for friendship, and I’m not allowed to contact anyone connected to the prisoner or give any type of gifts. This is new to me, and although I’ve written to both of them twice, I haven’t heard back yet from either of them. (With the many stops each letter makes before getting from one person to another, this isn’t unusual.) 

I’ve been asking myself in what ways I could be useful or helpful to people in need. This is a small thing I can do that could have a huge impact on one person. Many prisoners don’t get visits or mail. Having their name called for mail actually helps in the way they’re treated by guards and other inmates — it shows they matter to someone on the outside, which is it’s own type of protection. Also, inmates who receive letters have a lower rate of re-incarceration. If you are interested or have questions, I’m happy to talk about it. #prisonpenpals #orderofmalta #penpals #stationery #drawyourselfcalm

This morning my dog and my puppy found a bat in the yard. It’s injured, poor thing, and I don’t know if it bit either dog. (Tiny mouth, I just don’t see anything.) Mako has had her rabies shots, but John is still too little. I’m waiting to hear back from the county health department about getting the bat tested. IF it is rabid, and IF John got bit and gets rabies, there is nothing to do but put him down. So I’m just here on the floor holding my puppy and quietly falling apart.

Just learned that the bat the dogs had in the yard tested negative for rabies! Thank goodness! 

But I did learn that rabies is so prevalent in 24 West Virginia counties that they air drop an oral rabies vaccine in bait to try to keep it down. Forest critters (mainly raccoons) eat it for immunity to slow the spread. I’ll feel much better after John finishes all his vaccinations! #rabies #rabiesvaccination #pethealth

New in the shop: Family name trays! 

I asked my husband his grandmas’ maiden names — no idea. I asked one of my daughters if she knew her Aunt’s name was actually HER Mom’s maiden name — nope. It’s so easy for us to lose those names, even though they’re a part of who we are. I made this pretty little tray to help start those conversations and help us remember. 

Using my own, for instance, it has our family name of Cooper, then my maiden name, Jay’s Mom’s maiden name, my Mom’s maiden name and then maiden names of all four Grandmas. (This doesn’t leave out the men, all those women got their Dads’ last names!) 

If you’d like your own, visit my shop on Etsy. (Link in my profile or search CoopCrafts. Use the code IGSENTME (like IG sent me) to save $5 this week only. #personalized #genealogy #familytree #heritage #ancestry

Watching the news this morning, my mind wandered after hearing the cheers in Texas as they voted to move forward a bill to make more powerful guns harder to buy. 

I live in a small but wealthy area of West Virginia. (WV, wealthy?! It’s all relative, people.) The mayor and I were in high school together, and he does a great job. Drugs are a historically heartbreaking problem in our state. In 2017, they assigned a fourth of the police force to focus on the drug problem, working old drug warrants, focusing on drug hot spots and having the entire force ask to search vehicles during routine stops. They TALK about it, and has it helped to have a reputation for being tough on drugs? It sure hasn’t hurt. 

The park had a skate park up high on the hill, kind of hidden away. It became a problem, drug paraphernalia scattered around. The skate park was closed, then a local kid emailed the mayor wanting a place to ride his scooter. They built a better skate park in the same city park, but this time it’s at the park entrance, brightly lit and visible to town traffic and the park users. It’s the coolest thing to see kids swooping around as you drive by. I want to pack a lunch and just sit and watch them glide by. 

We do need to do something about guns. The law in Texas is unlikely to pass. But let’s talk about it. Let’s think about what would make it better. Sometimes a skate park just needs to be seen. Sometimes guns just need to be sold with a little more information. 

That’s my #lavameetsseaquilt , just there hoping you’d care to read. 👋🏻

We received John’s DNA results. He is 0% Border Collie, which surprised us! 

He actually is:
19% Husky
16% Pit Bull 
9% German Shepherd Dog 
9% Australian Cattle Dog

And a mix of others that includes 6% Chihuahua?! 

It was also interesting to read his traits, such as the fact that he will be a huge seasonal shedder. 😝 I most appreciate the health data, which showed he is negative for genes that make him likely to not handle anesthesia well. (Very important to me, he has surgery next week.) 

His family tree also showed us one of his parents was half Husky mixed with mainly German Shepherd Dog. Since we were able to meet his Mom and that’s just what she looked like, I have faith that the information is correct. Dad was mostly a Pit Bull, like most WV shelter dogs.  #wisdompanel #dogdna #mydogisnamedjohn #adoptdontshop #huskypit

Got to have Mary in the #churchroombox ! 

Have you heard that there have been some church members who have argued with pastors after hearing the #sermononthemount ? They’ve complained that it is “weak” to turn the other cheek. Actually, the opposite is true. 

According to Jesus, if someone strikes you on the right cheek, you should turn and offer them the left, too. You are not being weak. The person who struck you has behaved terribly and “unleashed evil into the world.” If you hit back, the evil is doubled. The devil delights. But God expects you to be strong and mature in your faith. Accept that evil, overcome it within yourself, and it is no longer in the world. Turn the other cheek and you’ll confuse them, and hopefully you’ll take the chance to ask, “Are you OK?” De-escalate the situation. Instead of more evil out there, you turned it good. It is our job to recognize what is wrong and try to make it right. 

Anyway. #sermonover Found the little frame on Etsy and printed a tiny bit of a picture of stained glass to add Mary. Very happy with it. #dollhouse #roombox #catholicchurch

From my @storyworth post today: 

“Has Anyone Ever Rescued You, Figuratively or Literally?”

I grew up in a two story house with a finished basement. Basements are naturally air conditioned, and in winter we kept warm with a wood/coal stove with a cooktop. During a blizzard in the 1970s, we had a power outage that lasted for days. We hosted some neighbors and that stove kept us all toasty warm and well fed.

When I was a teenager, the basement had a thick foam couch and chair that could be unfolded into beds. I fell asleep on one watching MTV late at night, but was woken up by our black and white long haired cat, Lucky. Lucky climbed on my chest and growled at something over to my left. The lights were off, but in the illumination cast by the TV I could see a kind of formless shape between my head and the brick base of the stove. I thought it might be a mouse and didn’t want Lucky to kill it, so I waved my hand over it, trying to scare it off. I could see the shape move, a sinuous shift that followed the path of my hand.

Fear turned my stomach instantly to ice.

Mice do not move like that.

SNAKES move like that.

I slid slowly to my right, and Lucky moved in sync with me to the left, stepping off my chest to keep his position exactly as it was in relation to the snake. He growled with each breath and his fur stood out all over. I stopped for a moment to see that the snake wasn’t making a move on Lucky, then flipped on the lights as I flew upstairs yelling, “DAAAAD!!! DAAAAAD!!!”

I yelled, “Dad, COME DOWNSTAIRS NOW!!” My shouts woke him and called back that he’d be there in just a minute. I was in a panic for Lucky and said, “GET DOWN HERE NOW!” Not the way I normally spoke to my Dad, but Lucky was in a standoff with a snake.

Dad grabbed a shovel from the garage and dueled what we could now see was a fairly sizable copperhead snake. It struck at the shovel and Dad drove the shovel down hard. It took a few tries, but Dad dispatched with the snake.

Cheesecake shooters, for when cheesecake would be awesome but let’s be quicker and easier. 

Crush a pack of 9-12 graham crackers and pour into glasses. Add two tablespoons melted butter to the crumbs first if you prefer a set crust. 

Whip together a can of sweetened condensed milk with two 8 oz packs of room temperature cream cheese and spoon over crust. 

Top with cherry pie filling and chill. That’s it. #easydessert
